description:
Follow-up to notme-ae65a0 (M1, partial fix in this iteration).

The bounded fix: removed Google from TRUSTED_ISSUERS in verify-proof.ts because Google ID tokens carry `aud=<client-id>.apps.googleusercontent.com` which can't match notme's hardcoded "notme.bot" audience pin.

The proper fix: replace single-string audience pin with a per-issuer audience map. Skeleton:

```ts
type IssuerAudienceMap = Record<string, string | string[]>;

// Configured via env at module load
const ISSUER_AUDIENCES: IssuerAudienceMap = {
  "https://auth.notme.bot": "notme.bot",
  "https://token.actions.githubusercontent.com": "notme.bot",
  "https://accounts.google.com": env.GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID, // <client-id>.apps.googleusercontent.com
};

// verifyOIDC reads expectedAudience based on payload.iss
async function verifyOIDC(token: string, audienceMap: IssuerAudienceMap) {
  // ... parse iss ...
  const expected = audienceMap[iss];
  if (!expected) throw new Error(`untrusted issuer: ${iss}`);
  // ... existing audience check using expected ...
}
```

Migration:
1. Add IssuerAudienceMap type
2. Update verifyOIDC signature to take the map
3. Add Google back to the implicit trusted set via the map (presence in map = trusted)
4. Update /connections, /auth/oidc/login, /join callers to pass the configured map
5. Add wrangler.toml config: GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID env var
6. Tests for the per-issuer routing

Once shipped, Google ID tokens work end-to-end at /connections etc.

